Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Forte, Pan African Insurance, Sasini Are Active

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-08-04T15:33:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-04/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-forte-pan-african-insurance-sasini.html
Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
dropped for an eighth day, the longest losing streak since at
least January 2004, losing 2.4 percent to 778.94 by the 4 p.m.
close in Windhoek, the lowest close since Sept. 17, 2010.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index gained for the
third day, climbing 0.1 percent to 1,176.10 by the 3 p.m. close
in Accra, the highest close since July 27. The  Nigerian Stock
Exchange  All-Share Index fell for a third day, losing 0.3
percent to 23,745.22 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to an e-mailed statement from the exchange. Mauritius’s SEMDEX
Index advanced for the first day in three, climbing 0.4 percent
to 2,031.95 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , the biggest
increase since May 11. Kenya’s All-Share Index rose 0.1 percent
to 66.35 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Forte Oil Plc (FO NL) fell 96 kobo, or 5 percent, to 18.32
naira. The Nigerian fuel retailer previously known as African
Petroleum Plc reported a 73 percent decline in first-quarter
profit to 210.6 million naira ($1 million) for the three months
through March, from 791.4 million naira a year earlier, the
company said in a statement posted on the website of the
Nigerian Stock Exchange today.  Pan Africa Insurance Holdings Ltd. (PAIL)  , the Kenyan
unit of South Africa’s Sanlam Ltd., strengthened for a second
day, rising 25 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 32 shillings, the
highest close since July 28, after sinking below a key level of
an indicator used in technical analysis.  The company’s 14-day relative strength index closed at
21.07 on Aug. 2., below the 30 level that signals to some
technical analysts a security is poised to rise. The RSI, as the
index is known, identifies possible turning points in indexes or
securities by measuring the degree that gains and losses outpace
each other in a given period.  Sasini Ltd. (STCL)  , a Kenyan coffee grower, increased
0.05 shilling, or 0.5 percent, to 10.35 shillings, as prices of
coffee beans climbed 6.9 percent at the latest auction in the
East African nation.  To contact the reporter on this story:
